      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "CFD solver must have documented version control, regression test suite, and release validation against canonical benchmark cases.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2023R1 used under institutional SQA plan. Version-controlled solver with documented regression test suite covering laminar and turbulent benchmark cases. Release notes confirm no outstanding defects affecting rotating machinery or scalar transport modules relevant to hemolysis prediction."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must pass at least two published benchmark verification cases relevant to rotating flow and scalar transport.",
      "rationale": "Code verification confirmed against (1) Taylor-Couette flow analytical solution for rotating geometry and (2) manufactured solution for passive scalar transport. Both benchmarks reproduced within expected truncation error bounds, confirming correct implementation of governing equations for the hemolysis application."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) for primary QoI must be below 10% at the production mesh level.",
      "rationale": "Three-mesh GCI study performed following Celik et al. (2008) protocol. Production mesh of 4.2 million polyhedral cells yields GCI of 3.8% for the hemolysis scalar at the worst-case operating point (2.5 L/min, 3500 RPM), exceeding the required level and providing high confidence in spatial discretization adequacy."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must be documented with sufficient detail to reproduce boundary conditions in the CFD model, including fluid properties, inlet/outlet conditions, and rotational speed.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark experimental data (Hariharan et al. 2011) provides complete documentation of test conditions including glycerol-water analogue fluid properties, inlet velocity profiles, outlet pressure boundary conditions, and pump rotational speeds. All five operating points replicated in simulation with documented boundary condition mapping."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., normalized RMS error or validation metric V) must be computed and reported against experimental data for primary QoI.",
      "rationale": "Relative hemolysis index predictions compared against experimental measurements using normalized RMS error across 5 operating points. Mean absolute error of 9.2% and maximum absolute error of 14.7% both within acceptable bounds for MRL 2. Validation metric V computed per ASME V&V 20 framework confirms model within experimental uncertainty band at 3 of 5 operating points."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoI used in validation (relative hemolysis index RH) must be directly linked to the clinical endpoint and COU decision criterion.",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index RH is the direct regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1 vs. predicate device) and is mechanistically connected to erythrocyte damage through the power-law hemolysis model. The validation QoI is identical to the COU decision QoI, ensuring no gap between what is validated and what is predicted for the regulatory submission."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must be conducted on geometry, operating conditions, and fluid properties sufficiently similar to the COU device and conditions.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry under CPB-representative flow rates (2–6 L/min) and rotational speeds (2500–4500 RPM) using blood analogue fluid. The COU device is a Class II centrifugal CPB pump operating in the same flow-speed envelope. Geometric similarity confirmed via non-dimensional analysis; fluid rheology differences bounded by sensitivity analysis."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor; default acceptance at Gradation 1.",
      "rationale": "At Model Risk Level 2, numerical solver error beyond code verification is not required to be separately quantified. The solver verification activities (benchmark cases and GCI study) provide sufficient evidence that solver errors are not a dominant uncertainty source for this application."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2; analyst qualification and peer review provide adequate control.",
      "rationale": "Use error formally scoped out at MRL 2. Analyst qualifications documented (PhD-level CFD engineer with 8 years rotating machinery experience). Independent peer review of simulation setup and post-processing completed by second qualified analyst. No evidence of systematic use errors identified during review."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Selection of turbulence model and hemolysis power-law model must be justified against available literature and sensitivity analysis performed for key model form choices.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega turbulence model selected based on literature consensus for rotating machinery with adverse pressure gradients. Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model adopted following systematic review of available hemolysis model forms. Sensitivity analysis comparing SST k-omega vs. realizable k-epsilon shows less than 8% difference in RH at worst-case operating point, confirming model form uncertainty is within acceptable bounds for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 beyond documentation of nominal input values.",
      "rationale": "Model inputs documented at nominal values per COU specification. Formal uncertainty quantification of input parameters not required at MRL 2. Key geometric tolerances and fluid property variations bounded by deterministic sensitivity runs demonstrating RH predictions remain below acceptance threshold across plausible input ranges."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2; single representative test article acceptable.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark dataset based on single pump geometry tested at multiple laboratories. Sample-to-sample variability not formally characterized but inter-laboratory reproducibility of experimental data (CV < 12% across 5 labs) provides indirect evidence of test sample consistency. Formal test sample characterization not required at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2; qualitative equivalency argument sufficient.",
      "rationale": "Qualitative equivalency established between validation case (FDA generic pump, glycerol-water analogue) and COU device (Class II CPB pump, blood). Reynolds number matching confirmed at all 5 operating points. Hemolysis model applicability to whole blood justified by published calibration studies. Formal parameter equivalency mapping not required at MRL 2."
